{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1939"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.15,0.52,0.03,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1939"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3638"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44350"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three day history of severe poly-articular joint pain and stiffness, particularly in the mornings associated with muscle aches. Five days ago, she returned from a holiday in Cambodia. She denies eating from any outdoor vendors and drank from bottled water only. She had the relevant travel vaccines prior to departing and took prophylactic atovaquone/proguanil hydrochloride tablets. She has a medical history of alpha+- thalassaemia trait, but is otherwise in good health. She denies significant abdominal pain or diarrhoea. On physical examination, her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 38.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is a maculopapular rash on her trunk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malaria","Yellow fever","Chikungunya virus","Hepatitis A","Typhoid fever"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with symptoms suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Echikungunya virus\u003C/strong\u003E, a mosquito borne alpha virus. It is most often transmitted via the Yellow fever mosquito (\u003Cem\u003EAedes aegypti) \u003C/em\u003Eand Asian tiger mosquito (\u003Cem\u003EAedes albopictus), \u003C/em\u003Esimilarly implicated in dengue virus. The disease was first identified in Tanzania in 1952 and since then has spread globally, mainly in central Africa, the Americas and South East Asia. More than a million cases are reported annually. The chikungunya virus is not currently endemic in Australia, but this disease should be considered in travellers who have been to regions where the disease exists and return with the characteristic clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChikungungya\u2019s derivation is from the Tanzanian language, Makonde, and means \u2018walking bent\u2019 because of the polyarthralgias suffered by these patients. It is typically characterised by a rapid onset fever associated with arthralgias, myalgias, rash. The external ear redness may reflect chondritis associated with chikungunya. Patients may also experience faintness and more rarely complications of conjunctivitis and uveitis. Neonates and the elderly are typically high risk groups with sever chikungunya manifesting in neurological signs, myocarditis and multi-organ failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis is primarily based on history and examination with key laboratory findings below reduced lymphocytes and platelets. Diagnostic confirmation can be made through reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrently no vaccination exists for this virus, so preventative measures involve the use of insect repellent, wearing long sleeved shirts and pants as well as the use of bed nets (permethrin treated for further protection.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVaccinations for \u003Cstrong\u003Etyphoid\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis A \u003C/strong\u003Eare typically given prior to travel to Cambodia. Moreover, as she denies consumption of contaminated food/drink and given her clinical picture, Hepatitis A and typhoid are both less likely causes. As she was taking malarial prophylaxis and has medical history of alpha+- thalassaemia trait, which is suggested to have a protective effect against malaria, this makes the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Emalaria\u003C/strong\u003E less likely. \u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever\u003C/strong\u003E is not present in Cambodia so yellow fever is an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chikungunya virus infection is uncommon in Australia, but should always be considered in individuals who are unwell with fever, joint and muscle pains and who have recently returned from a region where the disease is endemic."],"references":["Moiz\u00e9is RNC, Fernandes TAAM, Guedes PMDM, et al. Chikungunya fever: a threat to global public health. Pathog Glob Health. 2018;112(4):182\u2013194. doi:10.1080/20477724.2018.1478777. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1080/20477724.2018.1478777","Weaver SC, Lecuit M. Chikungunya virus and the global spread of a mosquito-borne disease. N Engl J Med. 2015;372(13):1231\u20131239. doi:10.1056/NEJMra1406035. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMra1406035"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86160"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T10:23:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T10:24:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1939"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta